    <h2>1. Planetary Mixer Prices in India 2026 — Capacity-Wise Breakdown</h2>
    <p>The planetary mixer is the most versatile mixer machine in any bakery or commercial kitchen. Its unique mixing action — where the attachment orbits the bowl while rotating on its own axis — makes it suitable for everything from whipping cream and beating eggs to creaming butter, mixing cake batters, and kneading light to medium doughs. If you need one machine that does it all, a planetary mixer is your best starting point. For a detailed deep-dive, see our <a href="/blog/planetary-mixer-guide">planetary mixer guide</a>.</p>

    <p>Planetary mixers are rated by bowl volume in litres. The <strong>mixer machine price</strong> increases with capacity, but also varies dramatically based on brand origin — Indian-made planetary mixers are typically 40–60% cheaper than imported equivalents at the same capacity.</p>

    <h3>7-Litre Planetary Mixer Price</h3>
    <p>A 7-litre planetary mixer is the smallest commercial-grade option. It's suitable for home bakeries doing small batches, tiny cafes making limited quantities of cakes and desserts, and as a supplementary mixer in larger bakeries for specific tasks like whipping small quantities of cream or making specialty batters.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Indian brands (Spar, Kumar Industries, local OEM)</strong>: ₹25,000 – ₹50,000</li>
      <li><strong>Imported brands (Sinmag, Bear Varimixer)</strong>: ₹55,000 – ₹85,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Dough capacity</strong>: 4–5 kg per batch. <strong>Cake batter capacity</strong>: 5–6 kg per batch. <strong>Motor power</strong>: typically 0.25–0.5 HP. A 7L planetary mixer is adequate if your total daily production is under 15–20 kg of batter or dough.</p>

    <h3>10-Litre Planetary Mixer Price</h3>
    <p>The 10-litre planetary mixer is the entry point for serious small bakeries. It offers enough capacity for small-batch production of cakes, buttercream, cookie dough, and light bread doughs. This is the most popular size for home-bakery-to-commercial transitions — when your home kitchen mixer is no longer keeping up with demand.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Indian brands (Spar, Kumar, Maxima, local OEM)</strong>: ₹45,000 – ₹80,000</li>
      <li><strong>Imported brands (Sinmag, Bear, Electrolux Professional)</strong>: ₹85,000 – ₹1,40,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Dough capacity</strong>: 6–8 kg per batch. <strong>Cake batter capacity</strong>: 8–10 kg per batch. <strong>Motor power</strong>: 0.5–0.75 HP. At 10L, imported brands start to show their advantage in build quality — the gear systems are more robust, the bowls are thicker stainless steel, and the motors are better protected against overload.</p>

    <h3>20-Litre Planetary Mixer Price</h3>
    <p>The <strong>planetary mixer 20 litre price</strong> is one of the most searched mixer queries in India, and for good reason — 20 litres is the sweet spot for the majority of Indian commercial bakeries. It's large enough for real commercial production (12–15 kg of dough per batch), yet small enough to be operated by a single person without difficulty. Most standalone bakeries, cake shops, and small hotel kitchens in India run a 20-litre planetary as their primary mixer.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Indian brands (Spar, Kumar Industries, Maxima, Ekon)</strong>: ₹75,000 – ₹1,30,000</li>
      <li><strong>Taiwanese/Korean brands (Sinmag, Bear Varimixer)</strong>: ₹1,30,000 – ₹1,80,000</li>
      <li><strong>European brands (Hobart, Electrolux Professional, Sammic)</strong>: ₹1,80,000 – ₹2,20,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Dough capacity</strong>: 12–15 kg per batch. <strong>Cake batter capacity</strong>: 16–20 kg per batch. <strong>Motor power</strong>: 0.75–1.5 HP. The 20L capacity can produce roughly 100–150 kg of finished product per day with 8–10 batch cycles. This covers the needs of most small to mid-sized bakeries in India.</p>

    <h3>30-Litre Planetary Mixer Price</h3>
    <p>A 30-litre planetary mixer suits medium-sized commercial bakeries, hotel pastry kitchens, and catering units with moderate daily production volumes. It's the step up when a 20L is running constantly and you need more per-batch capacity to keep up with demand.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Indian brands</strong>: ₹1,10,000 – ₹1,80,000</li>
      <li><strong>Imported brands (Sinmag, Hobart, Bear)</strong>: ₹1,80,000 – ₹2,80,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Dough capacity</strong>: 18–22 kg per batch. <strong>Motor power</strong>: 1.5–2 HP. At 30L and above, floor-standing models become the norm — countertop models are rare above 20L. You'll need dedicated floor space, appropriate electrical connections (usually 3-phase power above 20L), and adequate ceiling height for the bowl to tilt and attachments to clear.</p>

    <h3>40-Litre Planetary Mixer Price</h3>
    <p>The <strong>planetary mixer 40 litre price</strong> is relevant for bakeries with high daily production — typically those making 200+ kg of finished product per day. At 40 litres, you're firmly in the professional heavy-duty category. These machines are built for continuous daily use, with heavy-duty gear drives, overload protection, and reinforced bowl supports.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Indian brands (Spar, Kumar Industries, Maxima)</strong>: ₹1,50,000 – ₹2,40,000</li>
      <li><strong>Taiwanese brands (Sinmag)</strong>: ₹2,50,000 – ₹3,20,000</li>
      <li><strong>European/US brands (Hobart, Electrolux Professional, Ferneto)</strong>: ₹3,20,000 – ₹3,80,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Dough capacity</strong>: 24–30 kg per batch. <strong>Motor power</strong>: 2–3 HP. A 40L planetary mixer requires 3-phase power. Weight ranges from 120–200 kg depending on brand, so floor reinforcement should be checked. These are serious production machines — not something you wheel into a corner and forget about.</p>

    <h3>60-Litre Planetary Mixer Price</h3>
    <p>A 60L planetary mixer is for high-volume commercial bakeries, large hotel pastry departments, and industrial cake or biscuit production. At this capacity, you can mix 35–40 kg of cake batter or 30+ kg of dough in a single batch.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Indian brands</strong>: ₹2,20,000 – ₹3,20,000</li>
      <li><strong>Imported brands (Sinmag, Hobart, Ferneto)</strong>: ₹3,50,000 – ₹5,50,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Motor power</strong>: 3–5 HP. These machines weigh 200–350 kg and require proper installation — including bolting to the floor in most cases. Bowl lifting is typically hydraulic at this size, making loading and unloading easier and safer. If you're spending ₹3 lakh+ on a mixer, the imported brand premium becomes easier to justify through longer service life, better motor protection, and lower total cost of ownership over 8–10 years.</p>

    <h3>80-Litre and 100-Litre Planetary Mixer Price</h3>
    <p>These are industrial machines for large-scale bakery factories, biscuit manufacturers, and institutional catering operations. At 80–100L, planetary mixers weigh 300–500+ kg and require dedicated infrastructure — heavy-duty electrical connections, reinforced flooring, and often custom ventilation for heat dissipation.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>80L Indian brand</strong>: ₹3,00,000 – ₹4,20,000</li>
      <li><strong>80L Imported brand</strong>: ₹4,50,000 – ₹6,50,000</li>
      <li><strong>100L Indian brand</strong>: ₹3,80,000 – ₹5,00,000</li>
      <li><strong>100L Imported brand (Hobart, Ferneto, VMI)</strong>: ₹5,50,000 – ₹8,00,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p>At this scale, most manufacturers offer customisation options — specific bowl materials, variable speed drives, automated ingredient addition systems, and programmable mixing cycles. Always get a site survey done before purchasing an 80L+ planetary mixer to ensure your facility can handle the electrical, structural, and spatial requirements.</p>

