    <h2>2. Spiral Mixer Prices in India 2026 — By Flour/Dough Capacity</h2>
    <p>If your primary product is bread, pizza dough, pav, buns, or any stiff-to-medium dough, a spiral mixer is almost certainly the right choice over a planetary mixer. Spiral mixers are purpose-built for dough — the rotating bowl and fixed spiral hook develop gluten efficiently with minimal heat buildup, producing cooler dough that ferments more predictably. For a full comparison, see our <a href="/blog/planetary-vs-spiral-mixer">planetary vs spiral mixer comparison</a>.</p>

    <p>Spiral mixers are rated in kilograms of dough (or sometimes flour) capacity. This can be confusing — always clarify whether the rated capacity refers to dough weight or flour weight, as they're very different. A "20 kg" spiral mixer typically handles 20 kg of total dough, which comes from approximately 12 kg of flour plus 8 kg of water (at 65% hydration).</p>

    <h3>20 kg Spiral Mixer Price (Approx. 12 kg Flour Capacity)</h3>
    <p>The 20 kg spiral mixer is the entry point for small commercial bread bakeries, pizza outlets, and bakeries that make pav, buns, and basic bread alongside their pastry line. It's compact enough to fit in smaller kitchens and affordable enough for startup bakeries.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Indian brands (Spar, Kumar Industries, Genius)</strong>: ₹80,000 – ₹1,40,000</li>
      <li><strong>Taiwanese brands (Sinmag)</strong>: ₹1,40,000 – ₹1,80,000</li>
      <li><strong>European brands (Ferneto, Famag)</strong>: ₹1,80,000 – ₹2,20,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Daily output</strong>: 200–320 kg of dough per day (10–16 batches in an 8-hour shift). <strong>Motor power</strong>: 1–1.5 HP. <strong>Electrical</strong>: single-phase or three-phase depending on brand. A 20 kg spiral mixer is sufficient for a bakery producing 200–400 loaves of bread per day or 500–800 pav rolls per day.</p>

    <h3>40 kg Spiral Mixer Price (Approx. 24 kg Flour Capacity)</h3>
    <p>The 40 kg capacity is the most popular spiral mixer size for established Indian commercial bakeries. It offers a good balance between per-batch output and machine cost, and can handle the production requirements of most standalone bakeries, pizza chains, and small bread production units.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Indian brands</strong>: ₹1,30,000 – ₹2,20,000</li>
      <li><strong>Sinmag / Taiwanese</strong>: ₹2,20,000 – ₹2,80,000</li>
      <li><strong>European brands (Ferneto, Famag, VMI)</strong>: ₹2,80,000 – ₹3,20,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Daily output</strong>: 400–640 kg of dough per day. <strong>Motor power</strong>: 2–3 HP. <strong>Electrical</strong>: three-phase required. At 40 kg, the difference between Indian and imported brands becomes more pronounced — imported spiral mixers typically have better bowl rotation mechanisms, more precise speed control, and better safety features (automatic stop on bowl open, thermal overload protection).</p>

    <h3>60 kg Spiral Mixer Price (Approx. 36 kg Flour Capacity)</h3>
    <p>A 60 kg spiral mixer is for serious commercial bread production — dedicated bread bakeries, large pizza operations, and bakeries supplying to multiple outlets or retail chains.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Indian brands</strong>: ₹1,80,000 – ₹2,80,000</li>
      <li><strong>Imported brands (Sinmag, Ferneto, VMI)</strong>: ₹2,80,000 – ₹4,00,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Daily output</strong>: 600–960 kg of dough per day. <strong>Motor power</strong>: 3–5 HP. At 60 kg capacity, you may want to consider removable-bowl models — they allow you to roll the full bowl away immediately after mixing and start the next batch, dramatically increasing throughput. Removable-bowl spiral mixers cost 20–40% more than fixed-bowl equivalents but can nearly double effective daily output.</p>

    <h3>80 kg Spiral Mixer Price (Approx. 48 kg Flour Capacity)</h3>
    <p>An 80 kg spiral mixer suits high-volume bread production facilities, large catering companies, and bakeries supplying to institutional clients (schools, hospitals, military canteens).</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Indian brands</strong>: ₹2,40,000 – ₹3,40,000</li>
      <li><strong>Imported brands</strong>: ₹3,50,000 – ₹4,80,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Daily output</strong>: 800–1,280 kg of dough per day. <strong>Motor power</strong>: 5–7.5 HP. At this capacity, most spiral mixers come with removable bowls as standard. Floor reinforcement is essential — an 80 kg spiral mixer with a full bowl can weigh over 500 kg during operation.</p>

    <h3>100 kg Spiral Mixer Price (Approx. 60 kg Flour Capacity)</h3>
    <p>The largest commonly available spiral mixer capacity. These are industrial machines for bread factories, large-scale pav production units, and industrial bakeries with continuous production lines.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Indian brands</strong>: ₹3,00,000 – ₹4,00,000</li>
      <li><strong>Imported brands (VMI, Ferneto, Diosna)</strong>: ₹4,50,000 – ₹6,00,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Daily output</strong>: 1,000+ kg of dough per day. <strong>Motor power</strong>: 7.5–10 HP. At 100 kg, you need dedicated industrial infrastructure — three-phase power with adequate amperage, reinforced concrete flooring, proper drainage (for washdown), and sufficient ceiling height for bowl-tipping mechanisms.</p>

    <h2>3. Dough Kneading Machine Prices in India 2026</h2>
    <p>Dough kneading machines are a distinct category from planetary and spiral mixers. These are simpler, purpose-built machines designed specifically for kneading dough — typically for Indian flatbreads (roti, chapati, paratha, naan), restaurant kitchen use, and basic bread dough mixing. They're less versatile than planetary mixers (no whipping or beating capability) and less refined than spiral mixers, but they're affordable, robust, and effective for their intended purpose.</p>

    <p>Dough kneading machines come in two main types: <strong>horizontal kneaders</strong> (with a horizontal arm that moves through the dough) and <strong>vertical kneaders</strong> (similar to a simplified spiral mixer). Indian manufacturers dominate this segment, and most machines are designed specifically for Indian kitchen and restaurant use.</p>

