    <h3>How to Read These Price Differences</h3>
    <p>The price gap between an Indian brand and a premium imported brand at the same capacity is typically 80–120%. This premium is justified by several tangible factors:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Motor quality and protection</strong>: Imported mixers typically use higher-grade motors with better thermal overload protection, meaning they can run for longer continuous periods without overheating. This matters if your mixer runs 8–12+ hours per day.</li>
      <li><strong>Gear system durability</strong>: The planetary gear mechanism is the heart of any planetary mixer. Premium brands use hardened steel gears with precision machining. Budget brands may use softer metal or less precisely machined gears that wear faster under heavy use.</li>
      <li><strong>Bowl and attachment quality</strong>: Thicker stainless steel bowls, better-polished surfaces (easier to clean), and more precisely made attachments that fit more snugly.</li>
      <li><strong>Safety features</strong>: Bowl guards, automatic stop on guard open, emergency stop buttons, and overload protection are standard on imported brands but may be optional or absent on budget brands.</li>
      <li><strong>Service life</strong>: A well-maintained Hobart or Sinmag mixer can last 15–20 years in daily commercial use. Budget Indian brands typically last 5–10 years under similar conditions.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The bottom line: if your mixer runs under 6 hours/day and your budget is tight, a good Indian brand is perfectly adequate. If your mixer runs 8+ hours/day in demanding commercial production, the imported brand premium is usually worth paying.</p>

